message:
@sam_potter I had to think about that too. It's like, "well, what did she want and did she get it?" And the answer is, yes, she toughed it out and got to the lights.

But, imagine that all she wanted to do was feel grass under her feet. (This would take some major rewriting, but hear me out.)  And, when she get down and does it, Flynn says, "If you like that, you'll never believe what the ocean feels like." And off they go. 

Would you still hold the same opinion that she is steadfast? No matter what else happened in the rest of the movie?

@sam_potter I think you've hit on the key moment that makes this movie screwy. You say she "almost gives in" -- but she gives in. She begs Gothel to save Flynn. So, she changes. Then Flynn cuts her hair off! He's changed from selfish to self-less.

There's a chaotic moment of "b.bb....bb... but I changed for you. Why are you changing for me?"

Add to that that Rapunzel is unhappy about her change, and then unhappy about his change!

@sam_potter I work in Hollywood and have had very little contact with Dramatica, and almost zero that wasn't dismissive (or derisive) of the theory. 

Many people know The Hero's Journey, although they know the watered-down Vogler version and not the actual Campbell version, which is also aggravating. Because, if you're going to learn something, learn it. Don't learn the Cliff Notes. But, even the people who know it tend to use it only to retroactively justify things.

I do think the two theories can work together. I actually think a writer can get a lot from reading every "how to" book out there. Usually they go to storyweaving, or can only be applied here and there.
